d bridges between disconnected jurisdictions and control the flow of babies across the Canada-U.S. border.Karen A. Balcom details the dramatic and sometimes tragic history of cross-border adoptions—from the Ideal Maternity Home case and the Alberta Babies-for-Export scandal to trans-racial adoptions of Aboriginal children. Exploring how and why babies were moved across borders, The Traffic in Babies is a fascinating look at how social workers and other policy makers tried to find the birth mothers, adopted children, and adoptive parents who disappeared into the spaces between child welfare and immigration laws in Canada and the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIntercountry adoptionxCorrupt practiceszCanada. 0aIntercountry adoptionxLaw and legislationzCanada. 0aIntercountry adoptionzCanadavCase studies. 0aIntercountry adoptionzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aIntercountry adoptionzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / Adoption & Fostering.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262114540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442621145423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442621145.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK